column3: Compensation required for or economic assessment required before regulatory taking (stricter than federal standard)? (=2 if both, =1 if one of the two, =0 if neither, multiplied by 0.5 if applies to state government only, not localities)
column4: State Wetland Restoration Program (=1 if yes, =0 if no)
column5: Wetland Regulatory Protection Statutes, Stricter than Federal (=1 if statewide, =0.5 if local/coastal, =0 if none)
column6: Endangered Species Regulations (=0 if no act or statute, =1 if act or statute, but only in regard to animals, =2 if act or statute in regard to both animals and plants)
column7: Guidelines for a State Development Plan (=0 if none, =1 if yes but no land-use element, =2 if yes and include land-use element)
column8: Strength of State Planning Role (=1 if weak, =2 if significant, =3 if substantial)
column9: State Mandated Local Plans (=1 if yes)
column10: Internal Consistency (=1 if state imposes requirement that zoning be based upon and consistent with the legally adopted comprehensive plan)
column11: Vertical Consistency (=0 if none, =1 if state merely assists localities, =2 if state imposes requirement that the local comprehensive plan of a city or county not conflict with plans of higher levels of government within the state)
column12: Horizontal Consistency (=0 if none required, =1 if state merely assists localities, =2 if state requires intergovernmental coordination among neighboring jurisdictions)
column13: Gasoline tax rate per gallon in dollars, including sales, excise, storage, and franchise taxes
column14: Consumer Price Index, All Items, Annual
column16: Active cap on greenhouse gas emissions from electric power producers? (1=yes, 0=no) (note: setting a goal or initiating a process doesn't count - only actual regulations in force)
column17: Wharton Residential Land Use Regulatory Index
column19: Mandated free speech on private property? (3=malls, universities, & neighborhood associations, 2=malls & neighborhood associations or malls & universities, 1=malls or universities, 0.5=some government connection required/signature gathering only, 0=none)
column20: state cost of living, index year 2007
column21: state implicit price deflator, index year 2008
column23: enacted eminent domain reform through legislation or initiative, or court decision putting strict limits on "public use" (=1 if yes, 0 if no, including judicial action)
column24: private property (=1 if prohibits private property taking for any private use, regardless of alleged public benefit, =0.5 if prohibits only some private-to-private transfers, =0 if no effective restrictions on this type of eminent domain use)
column25: blight (=1 if implemented stricter definition either explicitly or implicitly, =0.5 if retained vague definition but required higher standard of proof, =0 if otherwise)
column26: Constitution enshrines all additional restrictions on eminent domain (=1 if yes,=0 if no, =0.5 if only some restrictions on ED have been codified constitutionally)
column28: Mandatory renewable portfolio standard for electric utilities: if yes, minimum percentage of retail sales for which required; if no, zero (halved if applies only to investor-owned utilities, or averaged among standards for all types of utilities; scored "1" and then adjusted in year of enactment)
column29: Renewable portfolio standard exceptions (1.5=large or existing hydropower excluded, 0.5=natural gas, coal gasification, or nuclear included, 1=otherwise, phase-ins linearly interpolated)
column31: State appellate decisions containing phrase "land use," cumulative from 1/1/1920
column33: Court land use decisions index: flandum/apop*1000000
column34: Cook Partisan Voter Index by State (+D, used for imputing land-use regulation, linearly interpolated between elections)
column35: Accommodation GDP divided by all GDP in *previous* year (for imputation of land-use regulation)
column36: Effective number of competing jurisdictions per 100 sq mi
column37: Model-derived extension of fwrluri (based on regression results of fwrluri on various predictors)
column38: Law bans employers from banning guns on certain company property, such as parking lots? (1=yes, 0=no)
